#: ../../../contributing.rst:5
msgid "Contributing to Scrapy"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing.rst:7
msgid "There are many ways to contribute to Scrapy. Here are some of them:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing.rst:9
msgid ""
"Blog about Scrapy. Tell the world how you're using Scrapy. This will help "
"newcomers with more examples and the Scrapy project to increase its "
"visibility."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing.rst:13
msgid ""
"Report bugs and request features in the `issue tracker`_, trying to follow "
"the guidelines detailed in `Reporting bugs`_ below."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing.rst:16
msgid ""
"Submit patches for new functionality and/or bug fixes. Please read `Writing "
"patches`_ and `Submitting patches`_ below for details on how to write and "
"submit a patch."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing.rst:20
msgid ""
"Join the `scrapy-users`_ mailing list and share your ideas on how to improve "
"Scrapy. We're always open to suggestions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing.rst:24
msgid "Reporting bugs"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing.rst:28
msgid ""
"Please report security issues **only** to scrapy-security@googlegroups.com. "
"This is a private list only open to trusted Scrapy developers, and its "
"archives are not public."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing.rst:32
msgid ""
"Well-written bug reports are very helpful, so keep in mind the following "
"guidelines when reporting a new bug."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing.rst:35
msgid ""
"check the :ref:`FAQ <faq>` first to see if your issue is addressed in a well-"
"known question"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing.rst:38
msgid ""
"check the `open issues`_ to see if it has already been reported. If it has, "
"don't dismiss the report but check the ticket history and comments, you may "
"find additional useful information to contribute."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing.rst:42
msgid ""
"search the `scrapy-users`_ list to see if it has been discussed there, or if "
"you're not sure if what you're seeing is a bug. You can also ask in the "
"`#scrapy` IRC channel."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing.rst:46
msgid ""
"write complete, reproducible, specific bug reports. The smaller the test "
"case, the better. Remember that other developers won't have your project to "
"reproduce the bug, so please include all relevant files required to "
"reproduce it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing.rst:51
msgid ""
"include the output of ``scrapy version -v`` so developers working on your "
"bug know exactly which version and platform it occurred on, which is often "
"very helpful for reproducing it, or knowing if it was already fixed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing.rst:56
msgid "Writing patches"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing.rst:58
msgid ""
"The better written a patch is, the higher chance that it'll get accepted and "
"the sooner that will be merged."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing.rst:61
msgid "Well-written patches should:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing.rst:63
msgid ""
"contain the minimum amount of code required for the specific change. Small "
"patches are easier to review and merge. So, if you're doing more than one "
"change (or bug fix), please consider submitting one patch per change. Do not "
"collapse multiple changes into a single patch. For big changes consider "
"using a patch queue."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing.rst:69
msgid "pass all unit-tests. See `Running tests`_ below."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing.rst:71
msgid ""
"include one (or more) test cases that check the bug fixed or the new "
"functionality added. See `Writing tests`_ below."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing.rst:74
msgid ""
"if you're adding or changing a public (documented) API, please include the "
"documentation changes in the same patch.  See `Documentation policies`_ "
"below."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing.rst:79
msgid "Submitting patches"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing.rst:81
msgid ""
"The best way to submit a patch is to issue a `pull request`_ on Github, "
"optionally creating a new issue first."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing.rst:84
msgid ""
"Remember to explain what was fixed or the new functionality (what it is, why "
"it's needed, etc). The more info you include, the easier will be for core "
"developers to understand and accept your patch."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing.rst:88
msgid ""
"You can also discuss the new functionality (or bug fix) before creating the "
"patch, but it's always good to have a patch ready to illustrate your "
"arguments and show that you have put some additional thought into the "
"subject. A good starting point is to send a pull request on Github. It can "
"be simple enough to illustrate your idea, and leave documentation/tests for "
"later, after the idea has been validated and proven useful. Alternatively, "
"you can send an email to `scrapy-users`_ to discuss your idea first."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing.rst:96
msgid ""
"Finally, try to keep aesthetic changes (:pep:`8` compliance, unused imports "
"removal, etc) in separate commits than functional changes. This will make "
"pull requests easier to review and more likely to get merged."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing.rst:101
msgid "Coding style"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing.rst:103
msgid ""
"Please follow these coding conventions when writing code for inclusion in "
"Scrapy:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing.rst:106
msgid "Unless otherwise specified, follow :pep:`8`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing.rst:108
msgid ""
"It's OK to use lines longer than 80 chars if it improves the code "
"readability."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing.rst:111
msgid ""
"Don't put your name in the code you contribute. Our policy is to keep the "
"contributor's name in the `AUTHORS`_ file distributed with Scrapy."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing.rst:115
msgid "Scrapy Contrib"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing.rst:117
msgid ""
"Scrapy contrib shares a similar rationale as Django contrib, which is "
"explained in `this post <http://jacobian.org/writing/what-is-django-contrib/"
">`_. If you are working on a new functionality, please follow that rationale "
"to decide whether it should be a Scrapy contrib. If unsure, you can ask in "
"`scrapy-users`_."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing.rst:124
msgid "Documentation policies"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing.rst:126
msgid ""
"**Don't** use docstrings for documenting classes, or methods which are "
"already documented in the official (sphinx) documentation. For example, the :"
"meth:`ItemLoader.add_value` method should be documented in the sphinx "
"documentation, not its docstring."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing.rst:131
msgid ""
"**Do** use docstrings for documenting functions not present in the official "
"(sphinx) documentation, such as functions from ``scrapy.utils`` package and "
"its sub-modules."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing.rst:136
msgid "Tests"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing.rst:138
msgid ""
"Tests are implemented using the `Twisted unit-testing framework`_ called "
"``trial``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing.rst:142
msgid "Running tests"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing.rst:144
msgid ""
"To run all tests go to the root directory of Scrapy source code and run:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing.rst:146
msgid "``bin/runtests.sh`` (on unix)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing.rst:148
msgid "``bin\\runtests.bat`` (on windows)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing.rst:150
msgid "To run a specific test (say ``scrapy.tests.test_contrib_loader``) use:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing.rst:152
msgid "``bin/runtests.sh scrapy.tests.test_contrib_loader`` (on unix)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing.rst:154
msgid "``bin\\runtests.bat scrapy.tests.test_contrib_loader`` (on windows)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing.rst:157
msgid "Writing tests"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing.rst:159
msgid ""
"All functionality (including new features and bug fixes) must include a test "
"case to check that it works as expected, so please include tests for your "
"patches if you want them to get accepted sooner."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing.rst:163
msgid ""
"Scrapy uses unit-tests, which are located in the ``scrapy.tests`` package "
"(`scrapy/tests`_ directory). Their module name typically resembles the full "
"path of the module they're testing. For example, the item loaders code is "
"in::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing.rst:167
msgid "scrapy.contrib.loader"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing.rst:169
msgid "And their unit-tests are in::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../contributing.rst:171
msgid "scrapy.tests.test_contrib_loader"
msgstr ""
